    <item>
      <title>Great Performances</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/442/2024-09-16_great-performances</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/442/2024-09-16_great-performances</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 16 Sep 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hello, GovTrackers!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sorry for the belated email, but it’s busy up here on Capitol Hill.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The big drama is whether and on what terms the House and Senate vote to keep the government open when the new fiscal year dawns on October 1. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The general expectation is that there will be a “clean continuing resolution” — meaning legislation free from any provisions that either party would find objectionable — with a three month funding extension continuing at the same funding levels as the previous year, and with an expiration of that bill in December. At that point, Congress would pass another continuing resolution or enact appropriations bills to set funding levels and direct the Executive branch concerning Congress’s priorities.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Because of the way the parties work in the House of Representatives in the last decade or so, House Republicans have been trying to pass a six month continuing resolution that also contains an extraneous provision on elections. Democrats won’t vote for the bill, it also seems likely some Republicans would not vote for it, and that legislation could never pass the Senate. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At the same time, the handful of Republicans who are insisting on the longer Continuing Resolution and the election provision are refusing to vote for a clean Continuing Resolution. They are striving to make an ideological point about what it means to be a “real” Republican. It is not possible to satisfy their demands and enact the legislation — that is why they make the demand, as it draws a line in the sand between real and RINO Republicans. That distinction is useful when appealing to their base in the upcoming election as well as asserting power within their party.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In theory, the vast majority of Republicans who would support a clean Continuing Resolution would join with some Democrats and pass the bill. This is how politics have generally worked for the 20th century, with factional coalitions running the chamber when it becomes possible for a minority of the majority party to defect. But the hardline Republicans have worked to make collaborating with non-Republicans toxic: it cost the last three Republican Speakers their jobs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The ultimate result may be a suspension bill that requires a 2/3s vote to pass and is introduced at the behest of the Speaker and Democratic Leader. The Democrats will support it, so the question will be how many Republicans will support it. Many of them will be playing a game of chicken — voting no on the resolution but desperately hoping it will pass. Or the House could produce a rule that still has something they want, but it’s not so objectionable that Democrats in the Senate would reject it. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Isn’t politics fun?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;House Republican leadership &lt;a href="https://democraticwhip.house.gov/floor-resources/whips-weekly-preview"&gt;scheduled&lt;/a&gt; 38 floor suspension votes and seven bills subject to a rule, with additional legislation possible. The bills set for the floor have an anti-equality theme while many of the bills on suspension are related to health. There’s also a vote on an anti-anti-pollution bill.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;House committees are set to hold &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2024/09/16"&gt;32 proceedings&lt;/a&gt;. I’m most excited for Wednesday’s Rules Committee hearing on the House Rules, where members of Congress make their case for how the chamber’s rules should change in the 119th Congress. Nature Resources, Oversight, and Veterans Affairs Committees have dozens of bills set for markups. And the House Modernization Subcommittee has an excellent hearing scheduled on continuity of Congress — what happens to our democracy if something bad happens to Congress to the point where it cannot do its job.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate, ah, the Senate. On the &lt;a href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/2024/09/12/schedule-for-monday-september-16-2024"&gt;floor&lt;/a&gt;, expect nominations to remain a priority. They do other things, but don’t give much notice in advance.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In committee, Judiciary and Foreign Relations will be busy processing nominations. The Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs Committee will have a blockbuster mark-up, with 9 nominations, 35 bills of various types, and 18 postal renamings. Don’t miss their hearing on the risks of replacing non-partisan civilian employees with political appointees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But wait, there’s more!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Tuesday is Constitution Day, the day that delegates to the Constitutional Convention signed the Constitution in Philadelphia in 1787.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Wednesday, the Library of Congress is holding a hybrid public forum on Congress.gov where they will take &lt;a href="https://newsroom.loc.gov/news/library-of-congress-to-host-congress.gov-public-forum-on-sept.-18/s/3289c0fd-d00d-4d33-a86c-3f3fb032c494"&gt;your comments and feedback&lt;/a&gt;. If there’s data you want on Congress.gov this is the time to let them know. Follow the link to RSVP.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Thursday, Congress is hosting the Congressional Hackathon, an opportunity for citizens, civil society, journalists, developers, and everyone else to meet with legislative staff on building technology to open up and modernize the Legislative branch. Follow the &lt;a href="https://congressionaldata.org/rsvp-for-congressional-hackathon-6-0/"&gt;link&lt;/a&gt; to RSVP.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Instead of funding the government</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/441/2024-09-14_instead-of-funding-the-government</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/441/2024-09-14_instead-of-funding-the-government</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 14 Sep 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;h2&gt;What Didn't Happen This Week&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Congress was fairly busy this week, although not with the one thing they really need to be: funding the government before the clock strikes October. The proposed "continuing resolution" that Speaker Johnson planned to put on the floor this week would have funded the government at current levels through next March with a new proof of citizenship requirement when registering to vote. Enough Republicans balked, many out of fear that they would be blamed for a government shutdown when the combo fails in the Senate, that the bill was pulled. We expect legislators to reach a deal before a shutdown.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The proposed proof of citizenship requirement would have almost certainly &lt;a href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2024/07/11/house-bill-noncitizens-federal-election/74366347007/"&gt;prevented far more citizens from registering to vote than non-citizens&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;What Did Happen This Week&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;A whole bunch of anti-China bills. Like 30 of them. Many passed by voice vote, which functionally means there was no opposition. You can see those at the &lt;a href="https://x.com/HouseDailyPress"&gt;House Press Gallery&lt;/a&gt; X account. Examples include the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr554"&gt;H.R. 554: Taiwan Conflict Deterrence Act of 2023&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8361"&gt;H.R. 8361: Economic Espionage Prevention Act&lt;/a&gt;, and the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7589"&gt;H.R. 7589: ROUTERS Act&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Bills with recorded votes included:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1103"&gt;H.R. 1103: Hong Kong Economic and Trade Office (HKETO) Certification Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h405"&gt;413-3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8333"&gt;H.R. 1157: Countering the PRC Malign Influence Fund Authorization Act of 2023&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h401"&gt;351-36&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8333"&gt;H.R. 8333: BIOSECURE Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h402"&gt;306-81&lt;/a&gt;. This bill &lt;a href="https://www.reuters.com/markets/us/us-bill-restrict-business-with-chinas-wuxi-apptec-bgi-passes-house-2024-09-09/"&gt;punishes specific, listed genetic research companies for their ties to China&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr9456"&gt;H.R. 9456: Protecting American Agriculture from Foreign Adversaries Act of 2024&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h415"&gt;269-149&lt;/a&gt;. This bill expands the power of the federal government to review agricultural land sales if a buyer is from China, North Korea, Russia or Iran.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1516"&gt;H.R. 1516: DHS Restrictions on Confucius Institutes and Chinese Entities of Concern Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h408"&gt;249-161&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1398"&gt;H.R. 1398: Protect America’s Innovation and Economic Security from CCP Act of 2024&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h413"&gt;237-180&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr1425"&gt;H.R. 1425: No WHO Pandemic Preparedness Treaty Without Senate Approval Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h411"&gt;219-199&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7980"&gt;H.R. 7980: End Chinese Dominance of Electric Vehicles in America Act of 2024&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h417"&gt;217-192&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Grab Bag&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;These all passed by voice vote in the House this week:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s1608"&gt;S. 1608: Starr–Camargo Bridge Expansion Act&lt;/a&gt;. The bridge is in Rio Grande, TX. This goes to the President next for signing since it has now passed both chambers of Congress.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7701"&gt;H.R. 7701: No Russian Tunnel to Crimea Act&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr6513"&gt;H.R. 6513: COCOA Act of 2023&lt;/a&gt;. Not about chocolate, but elections and allowing Congressional observers at polling places.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Looking Within&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;These bills about Congress's own internal operations were of particular interest to us:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7593"&gt;H.R. 7593: Modernizing the Congressional Research Service’s Access to Data Act&lt;/a&gt;. This would give Congress's nonpartisan researchers greater ability to get access to confidential executive branch agency information if they keep it secret.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7592"&gt;H.R. 7592: To direct the Librarian of Congress to promote the more cost-effective, efficient, and expanded availability of the Annotated Constitution and pocket-part supplements by replacing the hardbound versions with digital versions&lt;/a&gt;. This bill would end the printing of copies of the Annotated Constitution and replace them with online-only versions.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt;      </description>
